      "name": "Gradient",
      "type": "Concept",
      "upstream_source_spans": [
        "The gradient ∇f(x) collects these partial derivatives into a vector."
      ]
    },
    {
      "mention_id": "ko_mention_dev_010",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_002",
      "name": "Gradient",
      "type": "Concept",
      "upstream_source_spans": [
        "∇h(x) = J_g(x)^⊤ ∇f(g(x))."
      ]
    }
  ],
  "evidence_catalog": [
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_001",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_001",
      "span": "Let \\(f:\\mathbb{R}^n \\to \\mathbb{R}\\) be a differentiable scalar-valued function. A partial derivative measures how \\(f\\) changes when one coordinate changes while the other coordinates are held fixed. The gradient \\(\\nabla f(x)\\) collects these partial derivatives into a vector. For a unit direction \\(u\\), the directional derivative is \\(\\nabla f(x)\\cdot u\\), so the gradient points in the direction of steepest local increase. A point where the gradient is the zero vector is called a stationary point."
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_002",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_001",
      "span": "Taylor approximation describes the local behavior of a differentiable function near a point. The first-order Taylor approximation around \\(a\\) is"
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_003",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_001",
      "span": "\\[\nf(a+h) \\approx f(a) + \\nabla f(a)\\cdot h.\n\\]"
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_004",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_001",
      "span": "For twice differentiable functions, a second-order approximation also includes the Hessian matrix, which describes local curvature. These approximations are useful because they turn a complicated function into a local linear or quadratic model. In optimization, this local model helps explain why the gradient gives a useful direction for changing the input."
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_005",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_002",
      "span": "Let \\(g:\\mathbb{R}^m \\to \\mathbb{R}^n\\) and \\(f:\\mathbb{R}^n \\to \\mathbb{R}\\) be differentiable functions. The composite function \\(h = f \\circ g\\) maps an input \\(x \\in \\mathbb{R}^m\\) to \\(f(g(x))\\). The chain rule describes how the derivative of the composite function depends on the derivatives of \\(f\\) and \\(g\\)."
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_006",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_002",
      "span": "For a differentiable vector-valued function \\(g\\), the Jacobian matrix \\(J_g(x)\\) collects all first-order partial derivatives of the output components of \\(g\\). It gives the best local linear approximation to \\(g\\) near \\(x\\)."
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_007",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_002",
      "span": "For the scalar-valued composite function \\(h(x)=f(g(x))\\), the multivariable chain rule can be written as"
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_008",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_002",
      "span": "\\[\n\\nabla h(x) = J_g(x)^\\top \\nabla f(g(x)).\n\\]"
    },
    {
      "evidence_id": "evidence_009",
      "lecture_id": "calculus_002",
      "span": "This formula shows how gradients and Jacobian matrices work together. The Jacobian transfers local changes in the input space of \\(g\\) into local changes in the input space of \\(f\\)."
    }
  ]
}
